# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-logic-apps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] With the increasing adoption of artificial intelligence (AI), organizations are implementing AI-driven technologies that can process natural language, interpret unstructured datasets, and interact with users.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] These systems are designed to adapt to new types of problems with reduced reliance on human intervention.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] A business process management system differs from BPA.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] However, it is possible to implement automation based on a BPM implementation.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] The methods to achieve this vary, from writing custom application code to using specialist BPA tools.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation (RPA) involves the deployment of attended or unattended software agents in an organization's environment.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] These software agents, or robots, are programmed to perform predefined structured and repetitive sets of business tasks or processes.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] Robotic process automation is designed to streamline workflows by delegating repetitive tasks to software agents, allowing human workers to focus on more complex and strategic activities.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] BPA providers typically focus on different industry sectors, but the underlying approach is generally similar in that they aim to provide the shortest route to automation by interacting with the user interface rather than modifying the application code or database behind it.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] Artificial intelligence software robots are used to handle unstructured data sets (like images, texts, audios) and are often deployed after implementing robotic process automation.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] They can, for instance, generate an automatic transcript from a video.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] The combination of automation and artificial intelligence (AI) enables autonomy for robots, along with the capability to perform cognitive tasks.
[src:azure-logic-apps/business-process-automation] At this stage, robots can learn and improve processes by analyzing and adapting them.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise application integration is an integration framework composed of a collection of technologies and services which form a middleware or "middleware framework" to enable integration of systems and applications across an enterprise.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Many types of business software such as supply chain management applications, ERP systems, CRM applications for managing customers, business intelligence applications, payroll, and human resources systems typically cannot communicate with one another in order to share data or business rules.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] For this reason, such applications are sometimes referred to as islands of automation or information silos.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] This lack of communication leads to inefficiencies, wherein identical data are stored in multiple locations, or straightforward processes are unable to be automated.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Applications can be linked either at the back-end via APIs or (seldom) the front-end (GUI).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The various systems that need to be linked together may reside on different operating systems, use different database solutions or computer languages, or different date and time formats, or could be legacy systems that are no longer supported by the vendor who originally created them.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In some cases, such systems are dubbed "stovepipe systems" because they consist of components that have been jammed together in a way that makes it very hard to modify them in any way.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] If integration is applied without following a structured EAI approach, point-to-point connections grow across an organization.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Dependencies are added on an impromptu basis, resulting in a complex structure that is difficult to maintain.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] This is commonly referred to as spaghetti, an allusion to the programming equivalent of spaghetti code.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] For example, the number of connections needed to have fully meshed point-to-point connections, with n points, is given by ${\tbinom {n}{2}}={\tfrac {n(n-1)}{2}}$ (see binomial coefficient).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Thus, for ten applications to be fully integrated point-to-point, ${\tfrac {10\times 9}{2}}=45$ point-to-point connections are needed, following a quadratic growth pattern.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] However, the number of connections within organizations does not necessarily grow according to the square of the number of points.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In general, the number of connections to any point is only limited by the number of other points in an organization, but can be significantly smaller in principle.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] EAI can also increase coupling between systems and therefore increase management overhead and costs.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is not just about sharing data between applications but also focuses on sharing both business data and business processes.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] A middleware analyst attending to EAI will often look at the system of systems.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] This section describes common design patterns for implementing EAI, including integration, access and lifetime patterns.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] These are abstract patterns and can be implemented in many different ways.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] There are many other patterns commonly used in the industry, ranging from high-level abstract design patterns to highly specific implementation patterns.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Here, the EAI system acts as the go-between or broker between multiple applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Whenever an interesting event occurs in an application (for instance, new information is created or a new transaction completed) an integration module in the EAI system is notified.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The module then propagates the changes to other relevant applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In this case, the EAI system acts as the overarching facade across multiple applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] All event calls from the 'outside world' to any of the applications are front-ended by the EAI system.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system is configured to expose only the relevant information and interfaces of the underlying applications to the outside world, and performs all interactions with the underlying applications on behalf of the requester.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Both patterns are often used concurrently.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The same EAI system could be keeping multiple applications in sync (mediation), while servicing requests from external users against these applications (federation).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] EAI supports both asynchronous (fire and forget) and synchronous access patterns, the former being typical in the mediation case and the latter in the federation case.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] There are two major topologies: hub-and-spoke, and bus.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Each has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In the hub-and-spoke model, the EAI system is at the center (the hub), and interacts with the applications via the spokes.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In the bus model, the EAI system is the bus (or is implemented as a resident module in an already existing message bus or message-oriented middleware).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Most large enterprises use zoned networks to create a layered defense against network oriented threats.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] For example, an enterprise typically has a credit card processing (PCI-compliant) zone, a non-PCI zone, a data zone, a DMZ zone to proxy external user access, and an IWZ zone to proxy internal user access.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Applications need to integrate across multiple zones.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The **Hub and spoke** model would work better in this case.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] , message bus) or implemented as a stand-alone program (i.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] e., does not use any middleware), acting as its own middleware.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] These are programs that know how to interact with an underlying business application.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter performs one-way communication(unidirectional), performing requests from the hub against the application, and notifying the hub when an event of interest occurs in the application (a new record inserted, a transaction completed, etc.).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Adapters can be specific to an application (e.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] g., built against the application vendor's client libraries) or specific to a class of applications (e.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The adapter could reside in the same process space as the bus/hub or execute in a remote location and interact with the hub/bus through industry-standard protocols such as message queues, web services, or even use a proprietary protocol.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] allow adapters to be created in a vendor-neutral manner.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] To avoid every adapter having to convert data to/from every other application's formats, EAI systems usually stipulate an application-independent (or common) data format.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] The EAI system usually provides a data transformation service as well to help convert between application-specific and common formats.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] This is done in two steps: the adapter converts information from the application's format to the bus's common format.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Then, semantic transformations are applied to this (converting zip codes to city names, splitting/merging objects from one application into objects in the other applications, and so on).
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] An EAI system could be participating in multiple concurrent integration operations at any given time, each type of integration being processed by a different integration module.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Integration modules subscribe to events of specific types and process notifications that they receive when these events occur.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] that conform to the EAI system's specifications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Currently, there are many variations of thought on what constitutes the best infrastructure, component model, and standards structure for Enterprise Application Integration.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] An independent data model based on a standard data structure, also known as a canonical data model.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] It appears that XML and the use of XML style sheets have become the *de facto* and in some cases *de jure* standard for this uniform business language.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] A connector, or agent model where each vendor, application, or interface can build a single component that can speak natively to that application and communicate with the centralized broker.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] A system model that defines the APIs, data flow and rules of engagement to the system such that components can be built to interface with it in a standardized way.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Although other approaches like connecting at the database or user-interface level have been explored, they have not been found to scale or be able to adjust.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Individual applications can publish messages to the centralized broker and subscribe to receive certain messages from that broker.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Each application only requires one connection to the broker.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] This central control approach can be extremely scalable and highly evolvable.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration is related to middleware technologies such as message-oriented middleware (MOM), and data representation technologies such as XML or JSON.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Other EAI technologies involve using web services as part of service-oriented architecture as a means of integration.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Enterprise Application Integration tends to be data centric.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In the near future, it will come to include content integration and business processes.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] In 2003 it was reported that 70% of all EAI projects fail.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Most of these failures are not due to the software itself or technical difficulties, but due to management issues.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Integration Consortium European Chairman Steve Craggs has outlined the seven main pitfalls undertaken by companies using EAI systems and explains solutions to these problems.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Shortage of EAI experts: EAI requires knowledge of many issues and technical aspects.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Competing standards: Within the EAI field, the paradox is that EAI standards themselves are not universal.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] EAI is a tool paradigm: EAI is not a tool, but rather a system and should be implemented as such.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Building interfaces is an art: Engineering the solution is not sufficient.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Solutions need to be negotiated with user departments to reach a common consensus on the final outcome.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] A lack of consensus on interface designs leads to excessive effort to map between various systems' data requirements.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Loss of detail: Information that seemed unimportant at an earlier stage may become crucial later.
[src:azure-logic-apps/enterprise-application-integration] Accountability: Since so many departments have many conflicting requirements, there should be clear accountability for the system's final structure.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] In computer programming, **event-driven programming** is a programming paradigm in which the flow of the program is determined by external events.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] User interface (UI) events from keyboards and mice, touchpads and touchscreens, and external sensor inputs are common cases.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Events may also be programmatically generated, such as from messages from other programs, notifications from other threads, or other network events.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programming is the dominant paradigm used in graphical user interface (GUI) applications and network servers.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] In an event-driven application, there is generally an event loop that listens for events and then triggers a callback function when one of those events is detected.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Event-driven programs can be written in any programming language, although the task is easier in languages that provide high-level abstractions.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Although they do not exactly fit the event-driven model, interrupt handling and exception handling have many similarities.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] It is important to differentiate between event-driven and message-driven (aka queue-driven) paradigms: event-driven services (e.g.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] AWS SNS) are decoupled from their consumers, whereas message/queue-driven services (e.g.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] AWS SQS) are coupled with their consumers.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Because the event loop that retrieves and dispatches events is common amongst applications, many programming frameworks provide an implementation of an event loop, and the application developer only needs to write the event handlers.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] The actual logic is contained in event handler routines.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] These routines handle the events to which the main program will respond.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] For example, a single mouse-click on a "Save" command button in a GUI program might trigger a routine to save data to a database.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] An "Exit" button might trigger a routine to exit the program.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] The event loop receives events from all such command buttons and other GUI elements, dispatching the appropriate event handler routine for each button.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Event handler routines need to be bound to specific events, so the event loop can dispatch the correct routine in response to the event.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Many IDEs simplify this process by providing the programmer with an event handling template for each specific event (such as a button click), allowing the programmer to focus on writing the event-handling code.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] In a sequential program, keeping track of execution order and history is normally trivial.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] But in an event-driven program, event handlers execute non-sequentially in response to external events.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Special attention and planning is required to correctly structure the event handlers to work when called in any order.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Most existing GUI architectures use event-driven programming.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] The Java AWT framework processes all UI changes on a single thread, called the Event dispatching thread.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Similarly, all UI updates in the Java framework JavaFX occur on the JavaFX Application Thread.
[src:azure-logic-apps/event-driven-programming] Most network servers and frameworks such as Node.js are also event-driven.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] A **low-code development platform** (**LCDP**) provides a software development environment – typically a graphical user interface (GUI) – that involves little or no writing of code.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] A low-coded platform may produce entirely operational applications, or require additional coding for specific situations.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Low-code development platforms are typically on a high abstraction level, and can reduce the amount of traditional time spent, enabling accelerated delivery of business applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] A common benefit is that a wider range of people can contribute to the application's development, not only those with coding skills, but good governance is needed to be able to adhere to common rules and regulations.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] LCDPs can also lower the initial cost of setup, training, deployment, and maintenance.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Low-code development platforms trace their roots back to fourth-generation programming language and the rapid application development tools of the 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Similar to these predecessor development environments, LCDPs are based on the principles of model-driven architecture, automatic code generation, and visual programming.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] The concept of end-user development also existed previously, although LCDPs brought some new ways of approaching this development.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] The low-code development platform market traces its origins back to 2011.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] The specific name "low-code" was not put forward until 9 June, 2014, when it was used by the industry analyst *Forrester Research*.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Along with no-code development platforms, low-code was described as "extraordinarily disruptive" in *Forbes* magazine in 2017.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] As a result of the microcomputer revolution, businesses have deployed computers widely across their employee bases, enabling widespread automation of business processes using software.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] The need for software automation and new applications for business processes places demands on software developers to create custom applications in volume, tailoring them to organizations' unique needs.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Low-code development platforms have been developed as a means to allow for quick creation and use of working applications that can address the specific process and data needs of the organization.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Research firm Forrester estimated in 2016 that the total market for low-code development platforms would grow to $15.5 billion by 2020.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Segments in the market include database, request handling, mobile, process, and general purpose low-code platforms.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Low-code development's market growth can be attributed to its flexibility and ease.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Low-code development platforms are shifting their focus toward general purpose of applications, with the ability to add in custom code when needed or desired.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Mobile accessibility is one of the driving factors of using low-code development platforms.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Instead of developers having to spend time creating multi-device software, low-code packages typically come with that feature as standard.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Because they require less coding knowledge, nearly anyone in a software development environment can learn to use a low-code development platform.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Concerns over low-code development platform security and compliance are growing, especially for apps that use consumer data.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] There can be concerns over the security of apps built so quickly and possible lack of due governance leading to compliance issues.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] However, low-code apps do also fuel security innovations.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] With continuous app development in mind, it becomes easier to create secure data workflows.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Some IT professionals question whether low-code development platforms are suitable for large-scale and mission-critical enterprise applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Others have questioned whether these platforms actually make development cheaper or easier.
[src:azure-logic-apps/low-code-development-platform] Additionally, some CIOs have expressed concern that adopting low-code development platforms internally could lead to an increase in unsupported applications built by shadow IT.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:azure-logic-apps/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] A **workflow engine** is a software application that manages business processes.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] It is a key component in workflow technology and typically makes use of a database server.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] A workflow engine manages and monitors the state of activities in a workflow, such as the processing and approval of a loan application form, and determines which new activity to transition to according to defined processes (workflows).
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] The actions may be anything from saving an application form in a document management system to sending a reminder e-mail to users or escalating overdue items to management.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] A workflow engine facilitates the flow of information, tasks, and events.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] Workflow engines may also be referred to as Workflow Orchestration Engines.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] A workflow engine is a core technique for task allocation software, such as business process management, in which the workflow engine allocates tasks to different executors while communicating data among participants.
[src:azure-logic-apps/workflow-engine] A workflow engine can execute any arbitrary sequence of steps, for example, a healthcare data analysis.
